china has made a breakthrough in preserving and replanting its broken fingers
xinhua news agency , jinan , january 18 ( reporter su wanming ) the cut fingers that have been successfully preserved in the -@ 196 degrees celsius nitrogen have been replanted after the operation .
a few days ago , chinese scholars announced a major breakthrough in the technique of preserving and replanting the cut fingers .
a few days ago , the hospital of the shandong provincial hospital once again successfully carried out the operation of a broken finger ( which has been preserved for five days in the -@ 196 degrees celsius liquid nitrogen ) . this is the second time that the hospital has successfully carried out the operation last year ( which has been preserved for 81 days in the liquid nitrogen of 196 degrees celsius ) .
the new consultation report on the medical and health science and technology project of the ministry of health confirmed that so far , only two cases have been successfully carried out in the world .
wang zengtao , director of the hand surgery department of the shandong provincial hospital , announced : " after a large number of animal experiments and research and the clinical application of the two cases , we have initially mastered the technique of cutting the finger and preserving the temperature . "
wang zengtao said that compared with the organs of heart , kidney , and so on , the composition and structure of fingers are more complicated , including many organizations such as blood vessels , nerve , muscle , skin , bones , key links , and tenacity , and is a kind of compound organization .
a series of complicated links , such as the preparation of cold storage liquid , the procedures for the freezing of organs , the restoration of temperature , the replanting of crops , and the prevention and treatment of the damage caused by the use of the technology , are involved .
the mastery of this technology has provided an important reference for the long - term preservation and successful revival of other human organs .
